issues.title: Intermediate Shaft (IMS) Bearing Failure
issues.description: The intermediate shaft bearing can fail catastrophically, leading to complete engine destruction. While less common in 991.1 generation compared to earlier models, some cases have been reported.
issues.fix_description: Complete engine rebuild or replacement required when bearing fails
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with high-quality oil, avoid extended storage without running engine

issues.title: Water Pump Failure and Coolant Leaks
issues.description: Water pump seals and impeller can fail, causing coolant leaks and potential overheating. Common issue affecting many 991.1 models.
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump assembly and associated seals, flush cooling system
issues.prevention: Regular coolant system inspections, replace coolant per maintenance schedule

issues.title: PDK Transmission Jerky Shifting
issues.description: PDK dual-clutch transmission exhibits jerky or harsh shifting, especially during low-speed maneuvers or when cold.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, clutch adaptation procedures, or clutch pack replacement in severe cases
issues.prevention: Regular PDK service intervals, allow transmission to warm up before aggressive driving

issues.title: Carbon Build-up in Direct Injection Engines
issues.description: Direct injection engines develop carbon deposits on intake valves, reducing performance and causing rough idle.
issues.fix_description: Walnut shell blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves
issues.prevention: Regular highway driving, high-quality fuel, periodic intake cleaning service

issues.title: Rear Main Seal Oil Leak
issues.description: Rear main seal develops leaks, causing oil to drip from the bellhousing area onto the ground.
issues.fix_description: Replace rear main seal, requires transmission or engine removal
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid overfilling engine oil

issues.title: Ignition Coil Failure
issues.description: Ignition coils fail prematurely, causing misfires and reduced engine performance.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty ignition coils and spark plugs
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, replace spark plugs per maintenance schedule

issues.title: Coolant Expansion Tank Cracking
issues.description: Plastic coolant expansion tank develops cracks, leading to coolant loss and potential overheating.
issues.fix_description: Replace coolant expansion tank and cap, refill cooling system
issues.prevention: Regular cooling system inspections, avoid overpressurizing system

issues.title: Air-Oil Separator (AOS) Failure
issues.description: Air-oil separator fails, causing excessive oil consumption and potential engine damage from oil starvation.
issues.fix_description: Replace air-oil separator unit and associated hoses
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, monitor oil consumption patterns

issues.title: Suspension Control Arm Bushing Wear
issues.description: Front and rear suspension control arm bushings wear prematurely, affecting handling and tire wear.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn control arm bushings or complete control arms
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive driving over rough surfaces, regular suspension inspections

issues.title: Electronic Power Steering Failure
issues.description: Electronic power steering system fails, resulting in loss of power assist and potential safety hazard.
issues.fix_description: Replace power steering motor or control unit
issues.prevention: Regular steering system inspections, software updates

editorial.tagline: The last naturally aspirated 911 with soul
editorial.hero_blurb: The 991.1 Carrera S represents the swan song of naturally aspirated 911 performance, delivering 400hp from its legendary 3.8-liter flat-six. This is your final chance to own a modern 911 that breathes freely and revs to 7,800 RPM with linear, predictable power delivery.
editorial.essence: The 991.1 Carrera S is the ultimate naturally aspirated 911, combining modern performance with the pure, linear power delivery that defined generations of Stuttgart's finest. It's the last of its kind, making it increasingly precious among enthusiasts who value throttle response over peak numbers.
editorial.heritage: The 991 generation marked Porsche's most significant 911 evolution since the original, growing in size while maintaining the essential character. The Carrera S continued the tradition of being the sweet spot in the 911 lineup - more powerful than the base Carrera but not as extreme as the GT models.
editorial.design_philosophy: Porsche aimed to create a more refined, daily-drivable 911 without sacrificing the raw connection that made previous generations special. The 991.1's design balanced modern comfort and technology with the visceral, mechanical feel that enthusiasts demand.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a direct racing derivative, the 991 platform spawned numerous motorsport variants including GT3, GT3 RS, and Cup cars. The naturally aspirated engine architecture traces its DNA directly to decades of Porsche racing success.
editorial.engine_character: The 3.8-liter DFI engine is a masterpiece of linear power delivery, building intensity smoothly from 3,000 RPM to its 7,800 RPM redline. Throttle response is immediate and predictable, with no turbo lag to interrupt the pure connection between right foot and rear wheels.
editorial.transmission_feel: The PDK dual-clutch offers lightning-fast shifts with satisfying mechanical precision, while the available 7-speed manual provides one of the last great rowing experiences in a modern sports car. Both transmissions perfectly complement the engine's linear character.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The chassis strikes an ideal balance between GT car precision and daily usability. Body roll is minimal, yet the suspension allows enough compliance for real-world driving while maintaining exceptional control and feedback through corners.
editorial.steering_feel: Electric power steering provides excellent feedback and natural weighting, responding immediately to inputs while filtering out unwanted harshness. The steering communicates road surface changes and grip levels with remarkable clarity.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive steel brakes provide strong, consistent stopping power with excellent pedal feel. The system offers impressive fade resistance and modulation, inspiring confidence whether on mountain roads or occasional track duty.
editorial.sound_signature: The naturally aspirated flat-six produces a distinctive metallic growl at idle that transforms into a piercing, mechanical howl at high RPM. With sports exhaust, it delivers one of the most intoxicating soundtracks in modern automotive history.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for driving enthusiasts who prioritize engine character over peak performance numbers and want a 911 that can serve daily duty while delivering weekend thrills. Ideal for collectors who appreciate the significance of the last naturally aspirated generation.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking maximum straight-line performance or fuel efficiency should consider turbocharged alternatives. Not suitable for buyers who prioritize practicality over driving experience or want the latest infotainment technology.
editorial.buyers_summary: Focus on finding examples with comprehensive service records and avoid high-mileage track cars unless thoroughly inspected. The naturally aspirated engine is robust but requires proper maintenance, and values are likely to appreciate as the last of its kind.

At £45,000, it's phenomenal value for a properly specified example that will likely appreciate as manual 911s become increasingly sought after.
